1. What happens when you initialize a repository? Why do you need to do it?

   a .git directory is created and populated. git init is required to create the .git structure
   so that file commits can be tracked and stored and the repositroy can be managed.

2. How is the staging area different from the working directory and the repository? What value do 
   you think it offers?

   The staging area is a temporary space for files that are to be comitted to the repository. Files
   may be added and reomved prior to executing a commit.

3. How can you use the staging area to make sure you have one commit per logical change?

   You can use git diff --stage to compare files in the staging area to those in the repository.

4. What are some situations when branches would be helpful in keeping your history organized? How 
   would branches help?

   Adding a new feature i.e. language, graphic, speed, etc. to an existing branch of code

5. How do the diagrams help you visualize the branch structure?

   Diagrams provide a big picture view of the branch structure making it easier to understand.

